l-to-do students is bunk. Public schools with large white enrollments continue to offer a good learning environment with good results. Public schools with large minority enrollments are dismal 8 hour daycare centers offering two free meals a day. Fifty years after the integration of America's public schools, it is now clear that the best predictors of this failed social experiment were not the rants and resistance of whites from both Birmingham and Boston and many places in between during the 60's and 70's, but from blacks in the mid 80's. It was at this time that many people began to both notice and talk about the lack of noticeable improvements of the black student after 15 to 20 years of integrated education. The answer and reason for these shortcomings according to the black 'experts' was not lack of effort on their part...not student or parent, but that &quot;the black child learns 'differently' than the white child'. If taken for their word, this truth sounds like a reasonable purpose  for segregation...for blacks to benefit from being educated in different schools from whites. Perhaps the most logical statement to ever be offered from the black community...even if it does blow up in their face. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1523" language="en" documentId="2462" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Charlie Michaels" date="Aug 29, 2013 10:15PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="13" thumbsDown="0" origId="2462" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1523"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>